<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-252-214  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 252 214.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  May 9 1989 v3 n19 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>System 7 dangles 'hooks.' (Apple's System 7.0 software) (featuresto be utilized by developers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Battelle, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Apple is relying on developers to build upon its System 7.0, whichcontains some innovative elements that add no functionality bythemselves, but can be utilized by developers to extend Macintoshsoftware capabilities.andP;  The platform is composed of such elementsas electronic-mail functions, a low-level interprocesscommunications (IPC) protocol and virtual memory capabilities.andO;The electronic-mail functions allow developers to add messagingfeatures directly into their applications and provide a basis fora store-and-forward server.andP;  The IPC protocol permits data sharingamong applications on the same machine or over a network, andvirtual memory capabilities allow up to 4Gbytes of magneticstorage space to be used as system memory.andP;  Other elements includeoutline fonts, a new printer architecture, a foreign file systemmanager and internationalization features.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   System 7.0 (operating system)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentSoftware EngineeringSystems SoftwareSpecificationsApplications Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   New Mac systems under construction. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>System 7 dangles 'hooks'andM;San Jose, Calif.andP;  -- In announcing specifications for new System-levelfunctionality and promoting object-oriented programming, Apple is attemptingto ensure that when it releases its new System, developers won't lag too farbehind with supporting applications.andM;Many of System 7.0's innovations will take the form of &quot;hooks&quot; that bythemselves add no functionality but can be utilized by developers to extendthe capabilities of Macintosh software.andP;  Apple will rely heavily onthird-party developers to bring new software to market expected until System8.0 is announced sometime in 1991.andM;Some users were disappointed that such capabilities will not be forthcomingyet.andM;&quot;I don't think anyone is interested in upgrading the hardware and softwareplatform of the Mac without an immediate major benefit like multitasking,&quot;said Steve Heinz, manager of office automation in the MIS group at a MotorolaCorp. facility in Phoenix, Ariz.andM;Still, most users were enthusiastic about new system features like IPC andvirtual memory.andP;  &quot;IPC provides tighter and tighter integration betweenapplications,&quot; said Peggy Cole, supervisor of manufacturing systemsdevelopment at General Dynamics' Data Systems Division in Pomona, Calif.andO;&quot;And virtual memory is easier to maintain and less costly than real memory,although, of course, we want both.&quot;andM;The conference, which runs through the end of this week, will featuresessions on C++, ATandamp;T's object-oriented extension to the C programminglanguage.andP;  Apple, which is developing a C++ implementation for the MacintoshProgrammers Workshop, last month told Mac developers that object-orientedprogramming will become the standard means of writing Mac software.andP;  Thecompany also said its development tools and systems software will eventuallybe merged in a unified object-oriented environment (see MacWEEK, April 18).andM;Sources close to Apple said the company will also announce pricing andavailability for CL/1, the SQL-based connectivity language developed byNetwork Innovations, now an Apple subsidiary, to link Macs to DEC VAXrelational databases.andM;Industry sources familiar with System 7.0 said that machines without at leastan '020 chip -- including the Plus, SE and, according to most reports,Apple's first laptop -- and MacIIs that have not been upgraded with a PagedMemory Management Unit (PMMU) will not be able to take advantage of allfeatures of System 7.0.andM;According to developers, the new system will provide a foundation for a newwave of powerful applications.andP;  &quot;These new technologies will allow us tobreak boundaries and create software that will take advantage of [Apple']hardware,&quot; said Gerald Caussade, president of Fairfield Software, a CL/1developer in Fairfield, Iowa.andP;  &quot;Right now we're bound by the current systemsoftware.&quot;andM;Developers and users expect Apple to provide a seamless path to the NewSystem.andP;  &quot;The Developer's Conference is a good place to introduce tools, butI hope the things Apple is announcing have a definite schedule&quot; for delivery,said Tom Evslin, president of Solutions Inc. of Williston, Vt.andM;If the new system cannot be run on older machines, Evslin said, he'd like tosee Apple provide a means of ensuring that applications that take advantageof System 7.0 are compatible with previous system versions.andM;From the business point of view, Claris' Dalal said, it will be &quot;tricky&quot; todevelop applications that survive the transition from System 6 to System 7,since the features of the new system are expected to be implemented insegments over the next six to nine months.andO;</TEXT></DOC>